segments.text: They had them for so long in a department head status.
Now, in those early days, did President Rutter or Vice President Page give you any guidelines, any boundaries?
None.
None.
How often did you meet with the other deans and the president and the vice president?
At that time, 59 and for a few years beyond that, there existed what was known, I think, as an executive committee, the executive committee.
President Rutter presided.
Other members were Vice President Page, Registrar Lloyd Heaton, who kept the minutes of that group.
Each of the four deans, academic deans, plus the dean of students,
and the vice president for business affairs.
That's one, two, three, four, five, six, I think eight people.
Well, they would meet, I believe, once a week over in the Koch building.
And the agenda consisted of curricular matters and other items which pertained to the operation of the university.
At times, there were some
Oh, let's see how to describe this.
At times there were some unexpected agenda items, but not frequently.
And by an unexpected agenda item, I mean something that one of the deans would bring to the table as a
as a potential problem in that area or whatever.
President Rutter had, President Rutter as the presiding officer of the executive committee
had the style of discussing an issue on the agenda, whatever it might be.
But then, before a vote was taken on it, and after, on occasions, he had expressed his view on the subject
He would go around the table asking each one of those present, what do you think?
And generally, you would say in a two-sentence expression, what I think.
And of course, they were always tailored to what the chairman thinks.
I recall there was one departure to that on one occasion.
after I'd been there a few years.
And it, I think, started the group.
Let's see.
But that was the way that President Rutter
made known to the deans what he expected in the way of change or progress or whatever.
Incidentally, Haskell, I don't know whether this should go into the record or not.
You want me to turn it off?
Yeah.
When you first got here, who were your dean colleagues?
My closest colleague was Fred Benson in the College of Engineering.
I did not know Patterson very well, dean of agriculture.
And
I knew Al Price somewhat, but not closely.
Describe Benson and his personality and his style.
Who?
Fred Benson.
Fred was low-key.
Thorough.
Took an engineer's.
Made an engineer's analysis about.
Issues that came up.
A stickler for truth and honesty.
Square shooter.
Do you think that President Rudder in those early, your early years here, do you think that there were any of the deans that had more influence with him than the others?
I've just named him Fred Benson.
I think Fred and his straightforwardness and his business acumen and knowledge of his field
plus the recognition that Fred had among the engineering sector in the state, commercial as well as collegiate, became known to Rutter, and he recognized that and respected it.
As you were trying to learn more about A&M and your responsibilities, to whom did you turn for input?
Who were your advisors, friends, counselors?
Haskell, I can't remember that I had one.
Did you pick up the phone and call another dean and say, I've got a problem, what do I do?
I'd call Benson occasionally, rarely.
Mm-hmm.
He was the only one I would call.
On maybe an occasion or two, I would call Wayne Hall, but not frequently.
He becomes the vice president not long after Boyd Page leaves.
Describe Wayne Hall's style of...
of administrative leadership?
Again, low-key.
That's the best I can say of it, a low-key guy.
He was strongly loyal to President Rutter, I think.
I've learned from him that he was Dean Hall.
I have trouble not calling him Dean Hall because when I worked for him as assistant graduate dean, but when I worked for Dr. Hall,
I learned that he apparently is the one when Mr. Rutter was very unhappy about the recommendation that the name be changed to Texas State University.
Mr. Rutter didn't like that at all.
And that Hall came up with the Texas A&M, no abbreviations, the A and the M and the ampersand, and that he said Mr. Rutter liked that.
He wanted to hold on to the A&M title.
Yeah.
With A&M not standing for anything.
That's right.
That's right.
I'm going to.
All right.
Unplug your.
Oh, I'm going to close this block.
As you became the new dean, what were your immediate goals for arts and sciences and then your long range goals?
No Haskell.
I don't recall having.
A set of.
Goals.
Either in writing or.
In memory.
I I wanted to.
First of all, I wanted to do a a good job.
I felt more responsible to the department heads and the faculty than I did to the Koch building.
And you didn't have any fires that had to be put out?
There were no immediate
problems that you had to deal with.
Well, quickly.
There were.
There were.
A couple of personnel matters.
That President Rudder was interested in in the School of Arts and Sciences.
That he wanted.
Changes made in.
But he didn't put undue pressure on me.
To.
Make those changes.
And they were made.
In time.
One ran its normal course, the other.
I found an opportunity where the individual had problems with his travel reports, and it was the basis for requiring a change.
It turned out well, and I think, please, Mr. Rutter,
But I wanted to see the college grow.
I wanted to see the departments get the recognition they deserved.
One of the first things I did from the standpoint of a study made to help me at the budget table

was to develop a statistical analysis of the budget of A&M College of Texas in which I showed total number of faculty by rank, salary and average salary by rank at each department in every college with college-wide summaries, school summaries, that is.
I also showed secretarial support in the department head's office for the department head and the faculty.
The number, the head count number of people in service positions to help the department head and the faculty.
And of course, here sits
ag and engineering, each with the support of being Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas, plus each with an engineering experiment station and an extension service from which
They could borrow and change and swap out and such.
And that was, incidentally, the amount of support for the departments in the School of Arts and Sciences almost just dwindled into insignificance when compared to these big guns.
I also did an analysis of travel funds, which was just startling.
Did an analysis of semester credit hour production, how much teaching took place in this college by department compared to that college by department.
That, when I went for my hearing with President Rutter on budget matters, and as I recall at that time the business manager was a chap by the name of Charles, Tom Cherry hadn't come yet.
Graber or something like that.
I believe it was G-R-A-E-B, I think.
Yeah, I think so.
I gave him a copy and I gave the president a copy and I went over it page by page and it was painful for them.
And I think that helped open the door budget-wise
for us in the School of Arts and Sciences.
We didn't make quantum leaps by any means, but we did increase our support both salary-wise and office help, travel, other expenses kind of things.
Gradually, but it increased.
Among your department, I'm not going to ask the negative now, among those department heads that you inherited, who were your favorites?
Hard to say.
Chester Clipple in mathematics.
thought was a great guy.
Chester did not take kindly at the graduate level in mathematics.
Chester did not look with great favor upon
making a strong effort to improve the graduate enrollment in mathematics.
His department was probably the most selective of all for graduate students.
He had grown up under the tutelage of a UT mathematician.
Name escapes me now.

who felt that you just almost had to walk on water to be a candidate, to be a doctoral student in mathematics, that you really truly had to come up with an original, creative, new mathematical construction of some kind that just never existed before.
Clipper was like that.
Now, who headed education when you arrived?
When I arrived, Grady Parker was head of education.
It was a department and business was a department.
It was a department.
Business was a division.
Oh, that's right.
The division of business.
No departments within the division.
And I was amused when, in a way amused,
I was amused at the rationale given for the dissolution of the School of Arts and Sciences into a College of Liberal Arts and a College of Science.
President Rutter said that various consultants had looked at it and they felt that the span of control
a good administrative word, that the span of control was too extensive for one dean to have so many departments, those in science and over here.
And at the same time that took place, I'd made a swap with political, a swap with the president.
I said, well, if we're going to do this, namely reorganize the College of
the School of Arts and Sciences and the two colleges.
I would like at least to take the Division of Business Administration and give it departmental status.
So in the same movement,
We created as many departments in business as we lost in science.
Span of control turned out to be the same.
So arts and sciences is divided into two parts at first.
Yes, liberal arts and science.
And did the geosciences go with science?
Oceanography and Meteorology.
Geosciences was comprised of oceanography and meteorology out of the School of Arts and Sciences.
Geology from engineering.
Geography from, was it in agriculture at that time?
Geophysics.
or was that Department of Geology?
But geosciences came, I think, after science did, maybe by a year, Haskell.
I'm fuzzy on that.
And then later, education becomes a college,
And business becomes a college.
Business becomes a college first.
Then education becomes a college in 69.
Okay.
So 10 years after you.
10 years after I got.
All right, let's back up and lead me as much as you can, lead this discussion through the century study, the aspirations report, and all of that.
How did, as far as you know, how did that come into being even?
What, the central council?
Why did we even have a forward look?
I think it came into being as a consequence of the University of Texas study.
Because theirs was their 75th.
Theirs was their 75th anniversary, wasn't it?
Yes.
That was the basis for the committee of 75.
and ours was the Century Council, 100.
Have to go up a little higher, you know.
So I think that was the prime push for the Century Council study.
President Rudder,

called me over and said he'd like for me to become the chairman of the coordinating committee i think was its title i'm not sure he gave me the names of others he thought would be good members of the committee and the responsibility of that committee was to
Determine agenda for meetings.
Seek out and put into usable form all the data and information which the various committees of the Century Council.
Salt.
Ask for.
Make it presentable to them.
I I. I guess the word would be.
I'm not sure, the first meeting of the Century Council, President Rutter asked me to lay out the long scope agenda, which I did.
And, of course, it was that Century Council supported by one other
not too frequently remembered activity that caused the big change in military and coeducation.
And with reference to that second one I'm speaking of, it was a study commissioned by the Farmer Students Association to go to the high schools of the state and
In a blindfold study, A&M not identified as the sponsor of the study.
They asked a PR firm, I think, in Houston to design and execute the study for them.
Barton Nelson was part of that over in rural sociology.
I know.
But that study, commissioned by the

at President Rudder and the board's request, commissioned by the former students and paid for by them, went to the high schools of Texas asking, I think, juniors or juniors and seniors about their preferences for colleges, why
Why do you prefer this college?
I don't know whether they asked, why do you dislike this college or not?
But nonetheless, A&M came out weakly, weak, weak, weak.
Such phrases as Cal College, no girls, and such as that.

I think that study, although it hasn't been given the recognition publicly that it deserves, I think that had as much influence on the dissolution of all military and the development of a coeducational program as anything else.
There's one other...
name associated with coeducation especially that I have not heard at all during any of the discussions over the years.
And that's the name of a woman by the name of Mary Ann Parker.
Do you know that name?
Mary Ann Parker was the wife of George Parker.
What was his name?
I knew them both.
Mary Ann, I think, was a UT grad.
Her parents, her family, I think, Parker Lumber and Parker Esten Hardware, that Parker, affluent, well-to-do, top of the list, O'Brien citizenship.
Mary Ann Parker
for several months raised all kinds of stew about the admission of women to Texas A&M University.
She was in President Rutter's hair and he, he was not happy with her pushing.
She wanted women admitted.
Oh Lord, yes.
She and Bill Moore.
I don't know what prompted Mary Ann to become so heavily involved, except that it might have been just it was something that she thought should happen.
But she threatened lawsuits.
and in fact may have initiated a lawsuit for a while back in the old Brown Eagle.
There's quite a few stories about Mary Ann Parker and her quest for the admission of women.
I never see her name identified with that movement, but it was strong.
Now, I have heard a legend
that when Mr. Rutter got our committee's first set of recommendations, recommending women, volunteer corps, that he called the deans in and fussed at them.
And did what?
And fussed at them, chewed them out.
Why didn't you all watch on the... Why don't you control it better?
There you go.
Is that correct, as you recall?
I do not specifically recall such a meeting.
It could have happened.
There are a lot of things I don't recall, Haskell.
Another part of the myth is that Benson, the way I heard it, Benson kind of said, well, Earl, if you didn't want their recommendations, you sure as hell shouldn't have asked for them.
That sounds like Benson.
Did you deans have any...
Did you all have any guesstimate of what the Century Study was going to recommend?
Were you all surprised?
Well, not really.
It seemed to me to be just such an essential
It's going somewhere along the line.
It's going to take place.
Why not now?
After all of this support for it and strong voices for it.
And of course there was that minority of the old diehards who.
Who resented it deeply?
But.
In the final analysis.
Did not submit a minority report.
Did any body try to twist your arm?
No.
No.
At one time, J. Harold Dunn was the chairman of the Century Council.
At one time, during a luncheon, I sat next to Harold, and he asked me, he said, Dean Hubert, he didn't say, do you think we ought to admit women?
He said, how do you think we should start the admission of women?
I said, well, Mr. Dunn, there are two ways in my mind.
The first is just use the same admission standards, but open it up.
If you're qualified, come on.
The second would be

a more gradual conservative approach, and that would be to open it up first for the first two to four years to transfer girls, students from junior colleges or from any other college who have at least 60 hours of college credit come to A&M for your degree and your upper division work.
And that was a move which I thought had some merit from the very beginning of this study.
I never did expound it, but I felt that it had some merit.
But I did say that to Harold Dunn.
He was the only one who asked me my opinion about the...
about the coeducational thing.
He was certainly for it, no question about that.
Now, I have the impression that one of the other unsung heroes in all those changes was Bill Moore.
Please add any information or perception you have of Bill Moore's interests and his role.
Well, I just, my knowledge of Bill's role is sideline knowledge.
not mainstream knowledge.
But I do know that Bill, and I've got to add, along with Mary Ann Parker, was just so strong in expressing their views on the need for A&M to open up as a coeducational school.
Bill Bill approached it from the standpoint of the.
Of the legitimate use of state resources.
You can't deny them on the basis of.
This discriminating on sex.
And.
That was essentially Mary Ann Parker's view also.
But Bill's main role, I think, was just as you indicated, some other individual put his arm around Earl and say, Earl, it's got to happen, old boy.
I can't keep the lid on the Senate anymore.
And of course, Bill was in such a strong position as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee
that he had to be listened to.
How Earl responded to that, I don't have the slightest idea.
What do you remember about any discussion or attitudes about race?
I don't remember much opposition to integration.
I don't think there was any.
I don't recall it if there was.
When were you aware that those first black students were going to enroll in summer school that year?
I didn't know that they were going to.
I certainly wasn't.
Huh?
I wasn't.
I wasn't aware, no.
I understand that Mr. Rutter called the Pentagon and said when they send some regular Army enlisted men, as they normally did to finish a degree at A&M,
to include some black students that summer.
And then he called Mr. Heaton in, I understand, and said, Lloyd, you check their prerequisites.
You check their transcript and be sure they're in the right section taking the right courses.
But I and my colleagues, we weren't aware that there were going to be any black students in history courses until
the appropriate instructors got a call from Mr. Eaton's office.
I wasn't aware of it, which is, I think, good.
Will you interview Charles McCandless?
Yes, sir.
I already have.
Did Charles tell you the story of the Pinkerton detective?
He mentioned it, but
Please, you tell it.
Charles was closer to it than I, but during the 60s, when the SDS was on campus and organizing the society chapter, they began to make noises which, of course, President Rutter detested.
And he tried to do everything he could to put roadblocks in their way.
Charles McCandless was the associate dean in liberal arts for student relations programs.
He came to me one day and said, Dean Hubert,
We have a new student who is just not going to class.
All he's done practically is register, maybe showing up in class once or twice, but he's not going to school at all.
What's his name?
He gave me his name.
I says, call him in and give him a warning and bust him out of here if he can't go to school.
I don't remember whether Charles.
Called him in and gave him the warning.
Or whether Charles first he must have done that.
Because a few days later, Charles got a call from the Coke building.
That that guy you're concerned about not going to class.
Don't worry about him.
He's on a special scholarship.
He is a Pinkerton detective from the Houston Pinkerton Detective Office, and he's here infiltrating the SDS group and reporting to President Rudder.
Did you have that information?
I don't think we did.
Talk to Chuck on it.
Oh, good.
Go back to Chuck and confirm that.
Does anybody know what the Pinkerton man discovered?
I don't.
And I doubt if Chuck does.
But he gave reports.
How frequently, I don't know.
But he took... You're mentioning McCandless.
Go back to your beginning months.
Who were your key staff people in your office?
Describe them.
Marie Franklo, the secretary.
Describe Ms. Franklo and come forward.
And...
And Skipper Schlesinger.
Schleselman.
Schleselman, the associate dean.
Shortly after I came on board, Skipper fell off of a ladder while painting his house.
He was in his 60s then.
Why he was up on a ladder, I don't know.
But nonetheless, he fell and broke a leg, as I recall.
And I had the dean's office for months with just Marie Franklo and myself.
Mrs. Franklo was such a joy.
She felt that the dean's office, wherever it was on campus, but that the dean's office was
the shining light on campus, and it had to be above reproach in every way.
For example, a little later on, we were able to hire a part-time
clerk to help Mrs. Franklow during Skipper's absence.
And the young lady came to work the first day without any hose on.
Mrs. Franklow sent her home and says, you go get some hose on.
You're working in the dean's office now.
But she was
She was very diplomatic with faculty, just outstanding with them.
She knew A&M and its entire history, I think.
She had good contacts throughout the college with other of her colleagues and others.
And she had a good communications linkage.
But she was a joy.
And she was a stickler for accurateness and thoroughness.
I remember one time I got a memorandum.
I've forgotten from which department.
In which there were a couple of misspelled words.
She sent the memorandum in without any comment.
I quickly identified the misspelled words.
Encircled him.
And I said, Miss Frank Lowe, send this back to the department.
And ask them to.
Revise the memorandum.
And send it over in a correct form.
Well, she was so pleased with that.
She says, that's grand.
But it was things like that that she thought was important to the dean's office.
Now, she was with you for how many years?
She was with me, Haskell.
She retired.
I'm trying to recall now.
When the College of Liberal Arts was organized in 65, I'm trying to remember what happened.
I think it was about that time that she retired.
And then she is followed by?
She was followed by Peggy Ritchie.
Peggy had been in a number of locations on campus.
Peggy had a degree from Lamar and had worked most recently for Bill Graff.
Oh, gosh, what a guy.
Nonetheless, I asked her if she would like to come over and join the new College of Liberal Arts.
She accepted and
and was a mainstay through liberal arts days and education too.
Competent, well educated, good solid record keeper, accurate, a stickler for perfectionist perfection.
And, yes, she was a younger Marie Franklo, really.
College of Liberal Arts.
I was amused.
Well, that's not the right word for it.
I'm amused now about it, but initially I was distraught.
I'm looking at my watch because I think shortly after 11 I'll need to go in, Haskell.
Okay, all right.
We're not far from the end of this tape.
Okay.
In 1970no, that's not it.
In 1995, the College of Liberal Arts celebrated its 25th anniversary.
